\begin_layout Subsection
The theory & practice of interest rate policy rule
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The CB determines the inflation rate over time (in the long-run).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Monetary policy can affect the output and employment only in the short-run
 (
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

around their potential levels
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

), by setting the interest rate.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The main goal is to 
\series bold
minimize short-run fluctuations
\series default
, as deviation fron the long-run levels.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
They key is to affect the output and the inflation expectations.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

potential level of output
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 is what would have been achieved with full employment and capital utilization.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A key assumption is that 
\series bold
monetary policy cannot change the potential output
\series default
.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The (un)employment level for measuring deviation from the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

potential output
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 is recently debated.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The potential log output can be estimated by the long-run trend of GDP.
 Then the 
\series bold
output gap
\series default
 is the (normalized) difference of the real GDP from the potential GDP.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
An alternative approach for the output gap calculation is to take the difference
 between the actual and the potential growth rate of the GDP.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The theory says that the objective function of the CB is to 
\series bold
minimize the deviation of the inflation (and the output - in log terms)
 from the target.

\series default
 It means that the goal is to set the interest rate, that would make this
 deviation as low as possible.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
The Taylor Rule
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
i_{t}=r^{*}+\pi_{t}+a(\pi_{t}-\pi^{*})+b(y_{t}-y^{*})
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $i_{t}$
\end_inset

 is the CB interest rate, 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi_{t}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi^{*}$
\end_inset

 are the inflation (actual, target), 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{t}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $y^{*}$
\end_inset

 are the output (actual, target).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It minimizes the inflation gap and the output gap.
 According to it, the CB should smooth the interest rate to reach the target.
 The nominal interst rate equals the inflation target, plus the weighted
 average of the inflation gap and the output gap.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Questions on implementation
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The determination of the inflation target is done both by the government
 and the CB (by law and by interpretation).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The weights of the deviations are determined mainly by the CB policy makers.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
An error term in the Taylor rule (
\begin_inset Formula $u_{t}$
\end_inset

) accounts for all 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

other considerations
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 than the inflation and the output.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In the long run the gaps equal zero (
\begin_inset Formula $u_{t}=0$
\end_inset

).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The inflation expectations tend to fulfill themselves, which is consistent
 with the Taylor rule (target anchoring).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The most important thing that allows CB to implement its policy - is having
 monopoly in the money market.
\end_layout

